Looking back at 2022 and reflecting on my journey as a mom. These are some Postpartum advice I wish I followed. 

——
1. I wish I wore a girdle or waist trainer or something. Everyone told me to but in the midst of being a new mom and my leg injury I spaced and I feel like it would of helped tighten things up a bit more… do any of you have experience when them? Did it work for you?

———
2. Creating an ACHIEVABLE workout plan and sticking to it. Yes I moved and yes I worked full time while figuring out how to be a mom with no mat leave but I could of done something just to move my body. I felt like when I started to workout again I was playing major catch-up.

———
3. I wish I would of stopped trying so hard to breastfeed. It was just not for us and although I had a bit of succemonth 2-3 Alina quickly lost interest. Not to mention it brought multiple mastitis and clogged ducts and lost sleep that frankly I didn’t need. Alina was perfectly fine with formula. She LOVED Bobbie and she made it very clear month 4 when she refused to breastfeed. Honestly it was a relief for me. I know some women just love it but it’s also ok to not. 

How was your postpartum experience? Any advice you wish you followed? 

#postpartumjourney #postpartumadvice #postpartum #newmommy

No knead Bread Recipe 
from the book “my bread” by Jim Lahey 

INGREDIENTS
bread flour 3 cups
table salt 1 1/4 tsp
instant or other active dry yeast 1/4 tsp
cool (55 to 65 degrees F) water 1 1/3 cups
wheat bran, cornmeal, or additional flour for dusting

1. In a medium bowl, stir together the flour, salt, and yeast. Add the water and, using a wooden spoon or your hand, mix until you have a wet, sticky dough, about 30 seconds.
Make sure it’s really sticky to the touch; if it’s not, mix in another tablespoon or two of water. Cover the bowl with a plate, tea towel, or plastic wrap and let sit at room temperature until the surface is dotted with bubbles and the dough is more than doubled in size. 12-18 hours.

2. When the first fermentation is complete, generously dust a work surface w/ flour. Use a dough scraper to put the dough on the work surface. It will be quite loose and sticky—do not add more flour, Use lightly floured hands or a bowl scraper or spatula to lift the edges of the dough in toward the center. Nudge and tuck in the edges of the dough to make it round.

3. Place a cotton or linen tea towel and generously dust the cloth with wheat bran, cornmeal, or flour. Gently lift the dough onto the towel, so it is seam side down. Fold the ends of the towel loosely over the dough to cover it and place it in a warm, draft-free spot to rise for 1 to 2 hours. The dough is ready when it is almost doubled. If you gently poke it with your finger, making an indentation about ¼ inch deep, it should hold the impression. If I doestit, let it rise for another 16 minutes.

Are you a mom that can relate? Dm me and let’s chat :) I feel down right frumpy almost everyday because as a mom and a full time small business owner I don’t have the luxury of focusing on myself because I have to focus and take care of everything else. I always come last. I know it’s my choice but it’s a necessary choice so I can make it through the day. So when what I like to call “mom frump” sets in, I’ve found these usually help me turn my mood around: 

1. Take down the mom bun, brush your hair. Run a straightner through it a bit. I like to throw in a bit of oil too to keep the ends looking nice. 

2. Put on foundation/ tinted spf/ cc cream (use your hands, you’re not going on a date)

3. Add some blush to cheeks, lids and lips (I’ll tag some great ones in the caption👇🏼)

4. Add a bit of liner or mascara or both

5. Spray your favorite perfume or use a scented body lotion or oil

6. Take a moment to stretch and reset

7. Put on your favorite dance song 

Any of these will help… all of these together will make you look & feel amazing 

❤️

Dark brown to dimensional blond hair color transformation Details 👇🏼

I’ve always wanted to try a lighter blonde but being a very dark brunette that has colored her hair quite a bit, didn’t make it easy! 

Then I moved to a new city and didn’t have the best experience trying to lighten my hair. I finally found @kmvhair that was able to correct my hair and lighten it as much as we could without damaging my hair so that we could get to the blind I wanted one day. It’s a marathon not a sprint.

Recently I went to vegas where one of my closest friends @hairbyleese does hair @thehairloungelv . She did my hair for years! She even did my hair for my wedding! So 6 hours later we were able to safely get my hair to my desired color. 

In part 2 I’ll talk about ways I’m nurturing my hair to keep it e healthy after lightening it so much.

How to prep for a pool day as a mom: 

1. A cute, flattering, kid friendly bathing suit (mine is @zarahome)

2. Hair oil: I use it because I recently lightened my hair and I don’t want the sun to dry it out more but it’s just good to use. I love @oribe @hairstorystudio 

3. Spf is a must: @eltamdskincare @shiseido @everedenbrand @naked_sundays @cocokind 

Make sure you’re getting into the hairline, neck, behind the ears, and chest

Not many people talk about the social media burnout. I know, poor us, that get to call this amazing opportunity a job. Trust me I understand and fully appreciate how lucky I am.

BUT for the last couple of years I’ve been miserable. Like REALLY MISERABLE and no longer enjoyed posting the way I used to. In part because I’m exhausted from keeping up with whatever hoop IG wants us creators to jump through but also because I became a mom and my priorities shifted. 

I want to be able to enjoy the memories as we are making them instead of watching them through a video I took. I don’t want to have my daughter see a phone glued to my hand because frankly that’s just what this job entails. 

So I started the year setting boundaries for my job. 

Just because it’s a social media job, doesn’t mean my life has to be lived on social media 24/7.

I choose to be present with my family, friends and daughter and care more that memories are made then captured. 

Trust me it was scary, and yes my paycheck did suffer because this app penalizes your engagement if you don’t spend hours engaging on the app yourself. So although I grew this community slow and stead since 2014… you only see whatever IG decides you should see. And I was tired of fighting against that. I don’t like that I can’t control my own career no matter how hard you work. So once I was ok with a reduction in income I felt like a weight was lifted. 

I didn’t feel the guilt I felt before. If I have an hour where I don’t want to work, I can take it. And trust me, mom needs an hour to decompress at the end of a long day of toddlers life, full time work and home duties. Before I felt like it was a missed opportunity to hustle. Now I know it’s better for my mental health to decompress. 

I just don’t want to regret not paying attention to my daughter growing up or being thankful for what we have. This world is changing and kids are growing up too fast. This is my way to slow things down a bit. 

I’m curious if you’ve noticed that I’ve been less present on here? Or what your general thoughts are?

Weekend adventures in Charleston, SC with our 2 year old toddler.

Baked

Walked the Ravenel Bridge as a family 

Hung out with the dogs

Took a long walk around I’on

Nothing can prepare you for kids. Am I right? 

Seriously though, you can read all the books, watched all the movies, take all the courses. But nothing will prepare you for the beautiful storm that will hit you so hard it will knock the wind of of you. 

And the funny part is, the blows just keep on coming! You think you made it through something… get ready, something else is going to challenge you. 

And the crazy thing is it affects EVERYTHING:

FAMILY

HOME

MARRIAGE / PARTNERSHIP 

FRIENDSHIPS

WORK

YOU TIME 

E V E R Y T H I N G…….

I remember both my husband and I felt so proud to make it through the newborn phase, then the baby phase and now toddler life is in full swing. 

She’s got sassy

She’s got vocabulary 

She’s got personality 

She knows what she wants but can’t often communicate it.

She’s a whole vibe and we are just simply trying to catch up 😅

The last couple months have been a challenge. I think we are hitting the “terrible 2s” which doesn’t immediately start when they turn 2 and apparently spans through the 3s. Joy! The tantrums are really and explosive and irrational and slightly funny, tho not in the moment (that’s just pure frustration and confusion and the need to make everything better).

This is a very challenging time. And I’m not even including potty training. That’s beast I don’t even want to tackle at the moment.

So what’s the 🔑 to raising a toddler for me? Personally it’s practicing patience and knowing this temporary and fleeting. And even the hard times will undoubtedly be remembered as a sweet moment. 

So yes, we are in the thick of it, but time with kids is something we will never get back and that is painful enough to even write it so I take every hard moment as a moment I will never get back. An opportunity to grow together, understand each other more, teach her the morals and life lessons I hope she holds dear one day and be there when she just needs a hug from mom. 

I’m curious what your take is on this phase of life with your littles?

With all the toys she has, one of her favorite activities is to paint random objects around the house while sitting on an old towel on the garage floor spending quality time together.

I realized that the more bells and whistles a toy has the quicker it looses its appeal. There’s no imagination needed with toys like that. Nothing to keep them engaged for longer. It might even be helping us create this stigma of very little attention span.

So my mom goal recently has been to do a “activity that doesn’t require many or any toys just some imagination” every single day. 

It’s not hard to see she looks forward to those moments other watching a favorite show or getting to@play with a toy. 

Time with our little ones is something we will never get back so why not make it count?
